              "text": "[[reply_to_current]]\nAbsolutely‚Äîhere‚Äôs a direct way to do it with **OpenClaw cron + gog**.\n\n## 0) Prep (once)\n- Authenticate `gog`:\n  - `gog auth credentials /path/to/client_secret.json`\n  - `gog auth add you@gmail.com --services gmail,calendar`\n- Make sure the OpenClaw Slack route is configured (from your normal Slack setup).\n- Get your Slack target ID, e.g. `channel:C1234567890`.\n\n## 1) Create 3 isolated check-in jobs (announce to Slack)\n\n> Use these commands in a terminal where `openclaw` is available.\n\nReplace:\n- `you@gmail.com`\n- `channel:C1234567890`\n- (optional) timezone if needed\n\n```bash\nopenclaw cron add \\\n  --name \"Claw Slack Check-in 09:00\" \\\n  --cron \"0 9 * * *\" \\\n  --tz \"America/Los_Angeles\" \\\n  --session isolated \\\n  --message \"Run daily 9am check-in. Execute:\n1) gog calendar events primary --account you@gmail.com --json --from \\\"$(date -u -d 'today 00:00' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\" --to \\\"$(date -u -d 'today 23:59' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\"\n2) gog gmail messages search 'in:inbox is:important newer_than:1d' --account you@gmail.com --max 20 --json\nThen post a short Slack-ready summary with: Today's calendar, priority meetings, and important unread emails. Keep it concise.\" \\\n  --announce \\\n  --channel slack \\\n  --to \"channel:C1234567890\"\n```\n\n```bash\nopenclaw cron add \\\n  --name \"Claw Slack Check-in 12:00\" \\\n  --cron \"0 12 * * *\" \\\n  --tz \"America/Los_Angeles\" \\\n  --session isolated \\\n  --message \"Run midday check-in. Execute:\n1) gog calendar events primary --account you@gmail.com --json --from \\\"$(date -u -d 'today 00:00' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\" --to \\\"$(date -u -d 'today 23:59' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\"\n2) gog gmail messages search 'in:inbox is:important newer_than:1d' --account you@gmail.com --max 20 --json\nThen post a short Slack-ready summary with any new high-priority commitments and important unread emails since morning.\" \\\n  --announce \\\n  --channel slack \\\n  --to \"channel:C1234567890\"\n```\n\n```bash\nopenclaw cron add \\\n  --name \"Claw Slack Check-in 18:00\" \\\n  --cron \"0 18 * * *\" \\\n  --tz \"America/Los_Angeles\" \\\n  --session isolated \\\n  --message \"Run evening check-in. Execute:\n1) gog calendar events primary --account you@gmail.com --json --from \\\"$(date -u -d 'today 00:00' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\" --to \\\"$(date -u -d 'tomorrow 00:00' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\\\"\n2) gog gmail messages search 'in:inbox is:important newer_than:1d' --account you@gmail.com --max 20 --json\nThen post a short Slack-ready end-of-day summary of remaining schedule + important email actions to take.\" \\\n  --announce \\\n  --channel slack \\\n  --to \"channel:C1234567890\"\n```\n\n## 2) Verify\n- `openclaw cron list`\n- `openclaw cron run <job-id>` (for any one job) to test immediately\n- `openclaw cron disable <job-id>` / `openclaw cron edit <job-id> ...` to tune later.\n\n---\n\nSmall caveat: some systems may not parse the `date -d` form exactly as written above (that‚Äôs GNU-style).               "type": "text",
              "text": "Short answer: **OpenClaw is a self-hosted, multi-channel AI assistant platform/bridge**. It runs a local (or server-hosted) **Gateway** that connects your chat apps and devices to a coding-capable agent runtime (Pi), then gives that agent memory, tools, and routing so it can act in your environment rather than just answer text.\n\n[[reply_to_current]]\n\n## What OpenClaw is\n\nOpenClaw is a control plane + orchestration layer for personal AI assistants. It is designed so you can:\n\n- Talk to your assistant from multiple messaging surfaces (WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, etc.)\n- Have one persistent service (the Gateway) coordinate sessions, policies, tools, and agents\n- Keep your data and workflows mostly on your own machine/network\n- Extend behavior via plugins/skills and configurable tool permissions\n\nIt‚Äôs built as an **always-on assistant backend** with an app/CLI/web-control surface.\n\n---\n\n## Core architecture (what‚Äôs under the hood)\n\n- **Gateway**: central process for WS/WebSocket control, channels, session routing, config, diagnostics, tools, and events\n- **Channel connectors**: per platform adapters (WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Google Chat, iMessage/BlueBubbles, Signal, Teams, etc.)\n- **Agent runtime**: Pi in RPC mode with streaming/tool-calling\n- **Workspaces + sessions**: per-agent workspace state, auth, model settings, and conversation histories\n- **Control surfaces**:\n  - CLI (`openclaw ...`)\n  - Web dashboard / WebChat\n  - macOS app + iOS/Android nodes (optional)\n- **Extensibility**: plugins and skills\n\n---\n\n## What it can do (capabilities)\n\n### 1) Multi-channel communication\nOpenClaw can receive and send through many chat platforms:\n- Core (often built-in): WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Google Chat, Signal, iMessage/BluBubbles, MS Teams, plus more\n- Extended/plugin channels: Matrix, IRC, LINE, Feishu, Nextcloud Talk, Nostr, Zalo, Twitch, and others\n\n### 2) Multi-agent routing and session isolation\n- Route messages by channel/account/peer/guild to different agents\n- Separate workspaces, credentials, session stores, and identities per agent\n- Useful for separating personal/work/family/role-based assistants\n\n### 3) Tool execution (what the assistant can actually do, not just talk)\nFirst-class tools include:\n- **Filesystem / process**: read/write/edit, exec/process\n- **Session tools**: list/history/send/spawn/inspect sessions\n- **Web tools**: search/fetch, optional browser automation\n- **Messaging tools**: send reactions/read/edit/delete/thread/permission actions etc.\n- **Node tools**: notifications, command execution on paired devices, camera/screen recording, location\n- **Cron & automation hooks**\n- **Gateway control**: restart/apply config/update itself in-place (when enabled)\n- **Image analysis**\n- Memory tools (`memory_search` / `memory_get`)\n\nTool access is configurable by allow/deny policies, profiles, per-agent overrides, and sandboxes.\n\n### 4) Long-running operations and control\n- Background process management (`exec` + `process` tools)\n- Cron jobs and wakeups\n- Automation triggers (webhooks, Gmail Pub/Sub, polling hooks)\n- Presence/health/troubleshooting telemetry and service management\n\n### 5) Media & media workflows\n- Receives/sends images, audio, documents via channels\n- Media understanding + transcription hooks available in the media/audio pipeline\n- Optional browser/canvas visual workflows\n\n### 6) Voice + mobile-device integration (optional)\n- Node pairing for macOS/iOS/Android\n- Actions like notification, canvas, camera/screen capture, voice wake/talk flows\n\n### 7) Self-hosted ops + security posture\n- Runs locally by default with explicit onboarding/config\n- Auth for Gateway (token/password), pairing/allowlists for inbound messages\n- Sandboxing (including per-agent policies), command approvals, channel policy controls\n- Works with remote access patterns (SSH tunnel, Tailscale) while keeping control-plane separation\n\n---\n\n## Domains it covers well\n\nThink of OpenClaw as a **personal AI operating layer** across these domains:\n\n- **Personal productivity**\n  - notes, reminders, schedule checks, email/web hooks, message triage\n- **Development / coding support**\n  - coding workflows, file edits, command execution, repo operations, browser-assisted tasks\n- **Ops / infra**\n  - service checks, logs, process management, monitoring commands\n- **Comms + support**\n  - operate across multiple teams/channels with unified bot presence\n- **Research / retrieval**\n  - web search/fetch + browser automation for structured extraction\n- **Home/edge device workflows** (via nodes)\n  - local device actions and media capture from paired devices\n- **Multi-identity agent orchestration**\n  - different assistants for different contexts/people/projects\n\n---\n\n## APIs and external services it integrates with\n\n### LLM / model providers\nOpenClaw supports many model backends (depending on config), including:\n- Anthropic, OpenAI, Qwen, OpenRouter, LiteLLM, Venice, Bedrock, Ollama, Together, Groq/Mistral/xAI/community-provider ecosystem (via provider configs), etc. (full list in `docs/providers`).\n\n### Chat/channel protocol integrations\n- WhatsApp (Baileys)\n- Telegram (grammY)\n- Discord (discord.js)\n- Slack (Bolt)\n- Mattermost (plugin)\n- iMessage (BlueBubbles recommended / legacy local CLI path)\n- MS Teams (Bot Framework)\n- Matrix, Signal, IRC, Slack/Chat APIs and more via supported/core channels and plugins\n\n### Tooling/platform APIs\n- Brave Search Absolutely‚Äîhere‚Äôs a direct way to do it with **OpenClaw cron + gog**.

## 0) Prep (once)
- Authenticate `gog`:
  - `gog auth credentials /path/to/client_secret.json`
  - `gog auth add you@gmail.com --services gmail,calendar`
- Make sure the OpenClaw Slack route is configured (from your normal Slack setup).
- Get your Slack target ID, e.g. `channel:C1234567890`.

## 1) Create 3 isolated check-in jobs (announce to Slack)

> Use these commands in a terminal where `openclaw` is available.

Replace:
- `you@gmail.com`
- `channel:C1234567890`
- (optional) timezone if needed

```bash
openclaw cron add \
  --name "Claw Slack Check-in 09:00" \
  --cron "0 9 * * *" \
  --tz "America/Los_Angeles" \
  --session isolated \
  --message "Run daily 9am check-in. Execute:
1) gog calendar events primary --account you@gmail.com --json --from \"$(date -u -d 'today 00:00' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\" --to \"$(date -u -d 'today 23:59' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\"
2) gog gmail messages search 'in:inbox is:important newer_than:1d' --account you@gmail.com --max 20 --json
Then post a short Slack-ready summary with: Today's calendar, priority meetings, and important unread emails. Keep it concise." \
  --announce \
  --channel slack \
  --to "channel:C1234567890"
```

```bash
openclaw cron add \
  --name "Claw Slack Check-in 12:00" \
  --cron "0 12 * * *" \
  --tz "America/Los_Angeles" \

  --announce \

  --to "channel:C1234567890"
```

```bash

```

Short answer: **OpenClaw is a self-hosted, multi-channel AI assistant platform/bridge**. It runs a local (or server-hosted) **Gateway** that connects your chat apps and devices to a coding-capable agent runtime (Pi), then gives that agent memory, tools, and routing so it can act in your environment rather than just answer text.

[[reply_to_current]]

## What OpenClaw is

OpenClaw is a control plane + orchestration layer for personal AI assistants. It is designed so you can:

- Talk to your assistant from multiple messaging surfaces (WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, etc.)
- Have one persistent service (the Gateway) coordinate sessions, policies, tools, and agents
- Keep your data and workflows mostly on your own machine/network
- Extend behavior via plugins/skills and configurable tool permissions

It‚Äôs built as an **always-on assistant backend** with an app/CLI/web-control surface.

---

## Core architecture (what‚Äôs under the hood)

- **Gateway**: central process for WS/WebSocket control, channels, session routing, config, diagnostics, tools, and events
- **Channel connectors**: per platform adapters (WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Google Chat, iMessage/BlueBubbles, Signal, Teams, etc.)
- **Agent runtime**: Pi in RPC mode with streaming/tool-calling
- **Workspaces + sessions**: per-agent workspace state, auth, model settings, and conversation histories
- **Control surfaces**:
  - CLI (`openclaw ...`)
  - Web dashboard / WebChat
  - macOS app + iOS/Android nodes (optional)
- **Extensibility**: plugins and skills

---

## What it can do (capabilities)

### 1) Multi-channel communication
OpenClaw can receive and send through many chat platforms:
- Core (often built-in): WhatsApp, Telegram, Discord, Slack, Google Chat, Signal, iMessage/BluBubbles, MS Teams, plus more
- Extended/plugin channels: Matrix, IRC, LINE, Feishu, Nextcloud Talk, Nostr, Zalo, Twitch, and others

### 2) Multi-agent routing and session isolation
- Route messages by channel/account/peer/guild to different agents
- Separate workspaces, credentials, session stores, and identities per agent
- Useful for separating personal/work/family/role-based assistants

### 3) Tool execution (what the assistant can actually do, not just talk)
First-class tools include:
- **Filesystem / process**: read/write/edit, exec/process
- **Session tools**: list/history/send/spawn/inspect sessions
- **Web tools**: search/fetch, optional browser automation
- **Messaging tools**: send reactions/read/edit/delete/thread/permission actions etc.
- **Node tools**: notifications, command execution on paired devices, camera/screen recording, location
- **Cron & automation hooks**
- **Gateway control**: restart/apply config/update itself in-place (when enabled)
- **Image analysis**
- Memory tools (`memory_search` / `memory_get`)

Tool access is configurable by allow/deny policies, profiles, per-agent overrides, and sandboxes.

### 4) Long-running operations and control
- Background process management (`exec` + `process` tools)
- Cron jobs and wakeups
- Automation triggers (webhooks, Gmail Pub/Sub, polling hooks)
- Presence/health/troubleshooting telemetry and service management

### 5) Media & media workflows
- Receives/sends images, audio, documents via channels
- Media understanding + transcription hooks available in the media/audio pipeline
- Optional browser/canvas visual workflows

### 6) Voice + mobile-device integration (optional)
- Node pairing for macOS/iOS/Android
- Actions like notification, canvas, camera/screen capture, voice wake/talk flows

### 7) Self-hosted ops + security posture
- Runs locally by default with explicit onboarding/config
- Auth for Gateway (token/password), pairing/allowlists for inbound messages
- Sandboxing (including per-agent policies), command approvals, channel policy controls
- Works with remote access patterns (SSH tunnel, Tailscale) while keeping control-plane separation

---

## Domains it covers well

Think of OpenClaw as a **personal AI operating layer** across these domains:

- **Personal productivity**
  - notes, reminders, schedule checks, email/web hooks, message triage
- **Development / coding support**
  - coding workflows, file edits, command execution, repo operations, browser-assisted tasks
- **Ops / infra**
  - service checks, logs, process management, monitoring commands
- **Comms + support**
  - operate across multiple teams/channels with unified bot presence
- **Research / retrieval**
  - web search/fetch + browser automation for structured extraction
- **Home/edge device workflows** (via nodes)
  - local device actions and media capture from paired devices
- **Multi-identity agent orchestration**
  - different assistants for different contexts/people/projects

---

## APIs and external services it integrates with

### LLM / model providers
OpenClaw supports many model backends (depending on config), including:
- Anthropic, OpenAI, Qwen, OpenRouter, LiteLLM, Venice, Bedrock, Ollama, Together, Groq/Mistral/xAI/community-provider ecosystem (via provider configs), etc. (full list in `docs/providers`).

### Chat/channel protocol integrations
- WhatsApp (Baileys)
- Telegram (grammY)
- Discord (discord.js)
- Slack (Bolt)
- Mattermost (plugin)
- iMessage (BlueBubbles recommended / legacy local CLI path)
- MS Teams (Bot Framework)
- Matrix, Signal, IRC, Slack/Chat APIs and more via supported/core channels and plugins

### Tooling/platform APIs
- Brave Search (web_search)
- Firecrawl optional anti-bot fallback
- Deepgram (transcription)
- Gmail Pub/Sub (automation input)
- Webhooks + cron scheduling
- Gateway HTTP APIs:
  - OpenAI-compatible chat endpoint (`/v1/chat/completions`)
  - OpenResponses-compatible endpoint (`/v1/responses`)

### Integration extensions
- Plugin ecosystem for extra channels, tools, and skills (ClawHub)
- Third-party command surfaces can be wrapped through tool plugins/skills patterns

---

## What makes OpenClaw unique

Compared to typical hosted chatbots:

1. **Gateway-first control plane**: one service handles channel ingress + routing + tool execution + sessions.
2. **True multi-channel, same assistant brain**: same assistant context across many apps, with per-agent isolation if needed.
3. **Local-first + open source**: you keep the process, config, and most data under your control.
4. **Actionable AI**: not just text replies; it can execute tools, run commands, use browser/nodes, and operate infrastructure workflows.
5. **Policy-aware agent design**: configurable tool restrictions and sandboxing by agent/session, allowing strong safety boundaries.
6. **Extensible architecture**: skills/plugins + node ecosystem let you expand into new channels/tools without redesigning the core.

---

If you want, I can also give you a **clean ‚Äúcapability map‚Äù by your use case** (coding, home automation, support bot, study/research) with a recommended starter config and what you should enable/disable first.
